The KwaZulu-Natal MEC for Transport, Community Safety and Liaison Bheki Ntuli launched the first of its kind driver testing technology which will assist in tackling fraud and corruption in Driver Licence Testing Centres (DLTCs) in the entire province of KwaZulu-Natal on Tuesday. This initiative dubbed e-driver is part of the strategic interventions to produce eligible and legitimate drivers with a view of reducing crashes and fatalities on the road. Ntuli together with the Police Provincial Commissioner, Lieutenant-General Khombinkosi Jula kick-started a day with an integrated cordon and search operation, raiding at the Durban CBD where they arrested 31 people found in possession of drugs and other dangerous weapons. The raid which was accompanied by the law enforcement parade, was a show of force and strength ahead of the festive holidays. wThe police raid was preceded by a visit to Rossburgh DLTC to launch the driver testing technology. The KZN province is the first province in the entire country to have this ground-breaking innovative system that will play a huge role in reducing road carnages. Ntuli said they decided to launch this system in Rossburgh DTLC because it was one of those DTLCs that was alleged to be